properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
The Threat is Reduced following the grassfire at Charlton-Jeffcott Rd, Wooroonook. 
  • This Advice message replaces the Advice message issued on 19 December 2025 at 8.15PM.
People located within Charlton, Woosang, Yeungroon, Yeungroon East are advised that normal activities can be resumed but you should still remain vigilant.

Impacts in your area: 
  • The following road remains closed: Charlton-St Arnaud Road.
  • Check the VicTraffic Website or call 13 11 70 for road closures. 
  • Emergency services will remain in the area and continue to monitor.
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.   

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service for assistance and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Goomalibee.
  • This Advice message replaces the Advice message issued at 8:53am Saturday 20 December.
  • The large grassfire that has been burning in Goomalibee, between Tarnook Road and the Broken River, is under control.
  • Emergency services remain working in the area.
  • Beware of dangerous tree hazards.
  • Only local traffic can travel in this area. See below for more information on road closures.
There is currently no threat to you, but you should stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do: 
  • Beware of dangerous tree hazards. Stay well clear of trees and do not walk under them.
  • Keep the roads clear so emergency services can respond.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Small fires may still be burning in this area.
  • Firefighters are patrolling the fire to completely extinguish it.
  • Heavy plant and machinery are operating in the area.
  • Smoke may still be visible from nearby communities and roads.
Local road closures are still in place. These are at:
  • intersection of Goomalibee Road and Tarnook Road
  • intersection of Tarnook Road and Burness Road
  • intersection of Terret Rd and Goomalibee Road.
Roads are now being assessed by Benalla Rural City Council for reopening soon.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

The next update is expected by 21/12/2025 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service for assistance and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Patchewollock, Willa.
  • There is a bushfire at Wyperfeld National Park - North South Track that is not yet under control.
  • The bushfire is travelling from North South Track in a north-easterly direction towards Jim Bathgate Rd and Hopetoun-Walpeup Road.
  • Sunday 21 December has been declared a day of Total Fire Ban for the Mallee.
  • This Advice replaces the Watch and Act issued at 2.16pm.
There is currently no threat to communities, but you should continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do: 
  • Monitor weather conditions and warnings. 
  • Review your fire survival plan. 
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Fire crews will remain in the area.
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 21/12/2025 09:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#VicFires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
